ife and Salary Changes ensures that coverage is updated annually based on salary adjustments, maintaining alignment with employee compensation. This dynamic ensures that benefits remain relevant and equitable over time [Data: Entities (15), Relationships (24, 29, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Voluntary Supplemental coverage allows employee-driven enhancements\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Voluntary Supplemental is an optional benefit that allows employees to increase their coverage in $10,000 increments, up to a maximum of five times their annual base salary. This flexibility empowers employees to tailor their insurance needs, increasing personal financial protection. The coverage limit is directly tied to the employee's salary, ensuring that higher earners can access greater protection, while maintaining proportionality. This feature enhances employee satisfaction and retention by offering customizable benefits [Data: Entities (16), Relationships (33, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Salary Changes drive annual recalibration of benefits\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Salary Changes are a critical process that occurs annually on the policy anniversary, which is determined by the employee's Date of Hire. This recalibration adjusts both Basic Life and Voluntary Supplemental coverage amounts based on the current salary, ensuring that benefits remain proportional to compensation. The process is governed by the Salary Changes entity, which acts as a bridge between salary data and benefit levels. This ensures that coverage evolves with the employee’s career progression and financial status [Data: Entities (17), Relationships (29, 33, 37, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Maximum Benefit cap ensures financial risk containment\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Maximum Benefit entity enforces a hard cap of $1,000,000 on total coverage, regardless of the sum of Basic Life and Voluntary Supplemental benefits. This cap is enforced by the Master Group Policy, which integrates the limit into the policy’s governing terms. The cap prevents unlimited liability for the employer and ensures that the insurance program remains financially sustainable. It also standardizes risk exposure across all employees, regardless of salary level or supplemental choices [Data: Entities (18), Relationships (27, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Date of Hire as the foundational trigger for coverage\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Date of Hire is the initial event that activates an employee’s eligibility for coverage under the group policy. It serves as the anchor point for the entire benefits lifecycle, determining the policy anniversary and the start of coverage. The relationship between Date of Hire and the EMPLOYEE entity confirms that eligibility begins precisely on this date, making it a critical data point for HR and benefits administration. Without this trigger, no benefits would be initiated, highlighting its foundational role [Data: Entities (21), Relationships (45, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Policy anniversary as the annual recalibration milestone\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The policy anniversary, which aligns with the employee’s Date of Hire, is the recurring event that triggers the annual review and adjustment of benefits. This date is used to implement Salary Changes, recalibrate Basic Life coverage, and reassess Voluntary Supplemental limits. The consistency of this timeline ensures uniformity across all employees and simplifies administrative processes. It also provides a predictable schedule for employees to anticipate changes in their coverage [Data: Entities (17), Relationships (37, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Interdependence of entities ensures system integrity\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The entire insurance framework functi